The Macedonians decided in a referendum on whether to change the name of their country
The people of Macedonia decided in a referendum on Sunday whether to change their name to “Republic of North Macedonia,” a gesture that would resolve a decades-long conflict with Greece, which had blocked its bid to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that its northern neighbor’s name is a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, both governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the Slav population, mostly in Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign has questioned whether participation will reach the minimum 50% required for the referendum to be considered valid.
The referendum paper asked the following question: "Is it in favour of joining NATO and the EU with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?"
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying for Macedonia, one of the countries emerging from the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to try to access bodies like the EU and NATO.
“Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, for the young people of Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the protection of the European Union, because this means a safer life for all,” said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it will not be legally binding, many Members of Parliament have said they will respect the result of the vote to make it decisive.
The change of name requires a two-thirds majority in Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission stated that no irregularities had been reported by 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% of the last parliamentary elections held in 2016, when 66% of registered voters cast their vote.
"I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe," said Gjose Tanevski, 62, who voted in the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko cast their vote in the Macedonian referendum on a country name change that would open the way for NATO and the European Union to join in Strumica (Macedonia) on September 30, 2018.
In front of Parliament, in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was preparing a small stage and pulling out chairs in front of the tents planted by those who were going to boycott the referendum.
"We are in favor of entering NATO and the EU, but we want to do it with our heads high, not through the back door," Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want us to enter as Macedonia, we can establish relations with other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership would provide the investment that Macedonia so much needs, whose unemployment rate is more than 20%.
"I think the vast majority will be in favor, as more than 80% of citizens are in favor of the EU and NATO," Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a positive result would be a “confirmation of our future.”
A poll published Monday by the Institute for Policy Research said that between 30 and 43% of voters would participate in the referendum, which means less participation than required.
Another survey conducted by Macedonia’s Telma TV revealed that 57 percent of respondents had planned to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote in favour.
For the referendum to be considered a success, participation must be 50% plus one vote.
Should it fail, it would be the first serious blow to pro-Western government policy since it came to power in May last year.
