John Edward: Language skills are fundamental for the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent educational centers have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary exam results that is reinforced by individual and collective successes harvested in the areas of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is noted that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in the centers.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, it reaches his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries, you cannot rely solely on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest passing rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS centres, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a fundamental competence that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
At present, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as the CTIM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in the curricula of independent colleges and everywhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Competencies revealed that 17 % of the reasons given by employers for the difficulties they encountered in covering jobs were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable in preparing young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities that require languages are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically outperform the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov among more than 4000 UK adults in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If they speak several languages, especially those in developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centers will focus on the most classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you can always choose between several languages taught by teachers specializing in this subject.
Independent educational centres in Scotland dedicate all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds for them.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages must be considered "competence for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges.
