U.S.-China trade war could benefit Beijing
The first rescues from the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and while there is still a long way to go before the battle ends, a break between the countries could benefit Beijing, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued the first warning earlier this year by imposing tariffs on major Chinese exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs affecting $200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion) in products, charging taxes on half of products entering the United States from China.
On all occasions, Beijing has taken equivalent retaliation, recently applying tariffs of about five to ten percent on US products worth $60 billion.
