Europe regained the crown when the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn scored the 14.5 points needed to defeat the United States.
American star Phil Mickelson, who had to fight for most of the tournament, threw his starting point into the water in hole 16 par 3, thus admitting his defeat to Francesco Molinari.
The Italian golfer Molinari stood out in all his rounds, becoming one of four players who have never achieved a 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
American Jordan Spieth lost 5 and 4 to the lowest-ranked player of the European team, Danish Thorbjorn Olesen.
The world's number one player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 and 1 to Englishman Ian Poulter, who could have played his last Ryder Cup.
Spanish Sergio García, a veteran who already holds eight Ryder Cups, became the European with the most tournament wins of all time, with 25.5 points in his career.
